         <fn id="d37527e140a1310">
            <label>2</label>
            <p>
               <mixed-citation id="d37527e147" publication-type="book">
The Analects, xvii.9.<fpage>9</fpage>
                  <volume>xvii</volume>
                  <source>The Analects</source>
               </mixed-citation>
            </p>
            <p>
               <mixed-citation id="d37527e162" publication-type="partial">
Lau's version
reads: "An apt quotation from the Odes may serve to stimulate the imagination,
to show one's breeding, to smooth over difficulties in a group and to give expres-
sion to complaint" (145)</mixed-citation>
            </p>
            <p>
               <mixed-citation id="d37527e177" publication-type="partial">
James J. Y. Liu translates the same passage as "It
can be used to inspire, to observe, to make you fit for company, to express griev-
ances" (109)</mixed-citation>
            </p>
            <p>
               <mixed-citation id="d37527e190" publication-type="other">
Liu 109-111</mixed-citation>
            </p>
